 (congregation applauding)

49
00:02:06,180 --> 00:02:07,500
 Well, hey, several weeks ago,

50
00:02:07,500 --> 00:02:10,360
 I got to do something that I thought I never would.

51
00:02:10,360 --> 00:02:14,620
 I got to co-pilot a private jet.

52
00:02:14,620 --> 00:02:15,920
 Now, admittedly, co-pilot is probably

53
00:02:15,920 --> 00:02:16,960
 a little bit of a strong word

54
00:02:16,960 --> 00:02:20,100
 because I know nothing about flying an airplane.

55
00:02:20,100 --> 00:02:22,240
 And yet for all intents and purposes,

56
00:02:22,240 --> 00:02:24,340
 that's essentially what I was doing

57
00:02:24,340 --> 00:02:27,840
 minus any of the actual control of the aircraft.

58
00:02:27,840 --> 00:02:31,020
 Like I was sitting in the cockpit of this plane

59
00:02:31,020 --> 00:02:33,260
 and I was experiencing everything

60
00:02:33,260 --> 00:02:34,540
 that the pilot was himself.

61
00:02:34,540 --> 00:02:35,860
 Like I'm sitting right there

62
00:02:35,860 --> 00:02:38,420
 and the plane steering wheel is like coming up

63
00:02:38,420 --> 00:02:40,700
 through my legs and I can hold on to that thing.

64
00:02:40,700 --> 00:02:41,940
 And then there's this dash in front of me

65
00:02:41,940 --> 00:02:43,220
 and all these meters and lights

66
00:02:43,220 --> 00:02:44,580
 and different kinds of readings

67
00:02:44,580 --> 00:02:46,260
 that I cannot make any kind of sense of.

68
00:02:46,260 --> 00:02:48,060
 And yet they're all right there in front of me.

69
00:02:48,060 --> 00:02:49,920
 I got the headphones on so I can hear everything

70
00:02:49,920 --> 00:02:52,140
 the air traffic control is saying to us.

71
00:02:52,140 --> 00:02:55,300
 And I looked to my left and there he is, the pilot himself.

72
00:02:55,300 --> 00:02:57,180
 Like this thing was awesome.

73
00:02:57,180 --> 00:02:59,260
 I'd never experienced anything like it.

74
00:02:59,260 --> 00:03:00,860
 And yet the reason it was so great

75
00:03:00,860 --> 00:03:02,860
 wasn't just because I'd never been on a plane before.

76
00:03:02,860 --> 00:03:03,980
 I'd been on a plane before.

77
00:03:03,980 --> 00:03:07,180
 Like I've ridden on the big commercial airplanes.

78
00:03:07,180 --> 00:03:10,860
 I grew up, my granddad, he flew a little prop plane.

79
00:03:10,860 --> 00:03:13,260
 And so I'd been in that sort of situation before

80
00:03:13,260 --> 00:03:16,700
 but I had never been in the cockpit of a private jet.

81
00:03:16,700 --> 00:03:20,540
 And so being in that environment changed everything for me

82
00:03:20,540 --> 00:03:22,820
 because the views are a little bit different from up there.

83
00:03:22,820 --> 00:03:23,660
 You know what I'm saying?

84
00:03:23,660 --> 00:03:24,480
 Like I'm sitting there

85
00:03:24,480 --> 00:03:25,900
 and I'm not looking out the side view mirror.

86
00:03:25,900 --> 00:03:28,140
 I'm looking out the front windshield

87
00:03:28,140 --> 00:03:30,220
 and I'm seeing everything that's happening.

88
00:03:30,220 --> 00:03:33,700
 And so we're sitting there and we pull out onto the runway

89
00:03:33,700 --> 00:03:37,060
 and we kind of line up and we get clearance

90
00:03:37,060 --> 00:03:38,380
 from air traffic control to go for it.

91
00:03:38,380 --> 00:03:39,980
 And so next thing you know, we're like a bullet

92
00:03:39,980 --> 00:03:41,660
 like racing down this runway

93
00:03:41,660 --> 00:03:43,520
 and the lines in front of us are speeding by.

94
00:03:43,520 --> 00:03:46,660
 And this jet is, it is accelerating so fast.

95
00:03:46,660 --> 00:03:47,700
 It was the coolest experience.

96
00:03:47,700 --> 00:03:48,540
 And the next thing you know,

97
00:03:48,540 --> 00:03:50,620
 he gently lifts us off the ground.

98
00:03:50,620 --> 00:03:53,300
 It was the moment I'd been waiting for.

99
00:03:53,300 --> 00:03:56,340
 And as we do like rain kind of begins to pelt our windshield

100
00:03:56,340 --> 00:03:57,620
 'cause it was sort of a dreary day.

101
00:03:57,620 --> 00:04:00,060
 And next thing you know, we get up into the clouds

102
00:04:00,060 --> 00:04:02,340
 and it's kind of a disorienting experience

103
00:04:02,340 --> 00:04:05,100
 because we're in these clouds and we can't see anything.

104
00:04:05,100 --> 00:04:07,340
 All we can see is the rain on the front windshield

105
00:04:07,340 --> 00:04:11,060
 until we broke through the clouds

106
00:04:11,060 --> 00:04:13,100
 and we reached our cruising altitude.

107
00:04:13,100 --> 00:04:16,420
 And as we went from a pitched ascent

108
00:04:16,420 --> 00:04:18,980
 to a flattened cruising altitude,

109
00:04:18,980 --> 00:04:23,420
 we found ourselves facing the most beautiful of settings.

110
00:04:23,420 --> 00:04:24,780
 I mean, this was the closest to heaven

111
00:04:24,780 --> 00:04:25,800
 that I'd ever seen before.

112
00:04:25,800 --> 00:04:26,720
 You know what I'm saying?

113
00:04:26,720 --> 00:04:30,540
 I am looking at white clouds beneath us

114
00:04:30,540 --> 00:04:33,040
 kind of billowing across like bubble wrap.

115
00:04:33,040 --> 00:04:34,280
 And then as you're looking around,

116
00:04:34,280 --> 00:04:35,780
 you can see out over to my right,

117
00:04:35,780 --> 00:04:39,620
 this massive storm cell and lightning cracking within it.

118
00:04:39,620 --> 00:04:41,100
 And then as I look over to my left,

119
00:04:41,100 --> 00:04:43,060
 you can see blue where there was no blue before.

120
00:04:43,060 --> 00:04:46,100
 Like this was the most amazing kind of scene.

121
00:04:46,100 --> 00:04:48,220
 And as I'm sitting there and I'm taking it all in,

122
00:04:48,220 --> 00:04:49,960
 I start to pepper the pilot

123
00:04:49,960 --> 00:04:51,460
 with my personal list of 20 questions

124
00:04:51,460 --> 00:04:52,940
 because this is the closest thing to flying

125
00:04:52,940 --> 00:04:53,780
 I'm ever going to get.

126
00:04:53,780 --> 00:04:54,780
 And so I've got a bunch of things

127
00:04:54,780 --> 00:04:55,980
 that I want to figure out.

128
00:04:55,980 --> 00:04:57,620
 And as he's answering all of them,

129
00:04:57,620 --> 00:04:59,900
 he said something that really stuck with me,

130
00:04:59,900 --> 00:05:01,840
 so much so that I wrote it down in my notes

131
00:05:01,840 --> 00:05:03,700
 'cause I wanted to make sure I could share it with you.

132
00:05:03,700 --> 00:05:06,260
 He said, "From the ground,

133
00:05:06,260 --> 00:05:09,380
 "it feels like the weather's always changing.

134
00:05:09,380 --> 00:05:14,140
 "But from up here, we know the sun is always shining."

135
00:05:14,140 --> 00:05:16,740
 And as he said that at 30,000 feet,

136
00:05:16,740 --> 00:05:18,460
 I thought of you, Porch.

137
00:05:18,460 --> 00:05:21,340
 You were on my mind as I flew in the cockpit of this plane

138
00:05:21,340 --> 00:05:24,360
 because I thought that's not just true to pilots,

139
00:05:24,360 --> 00:05:26,400
 that's true to you and me.

140
00:05:26,400 --> 00:05:27,460
 Like for many of you here,

141
00:05:27,460 --> 00:05:30,320
 it feels like the weather in your world is always changing.

142
00:05:30,320 --> 00:05:33,100
 Like one minute, the weather might be beautiful.

143
00:05:33,100 --> 00:05:33,940
 And the next thing you know,

144
00:05:33,940 --> 00:05:37,660
 it feels like a storm is shaking your reality.

145
00:05:37,660 --> 00:05:41,160
 And then you're next slipping into this sort of apathetic,

146
00:05:41,160 --> 00:05:45,140
 sort of moody gray weather sort of situation.

147
00:05:45,140 --> 00:05:47,660
 And yet, though the weather may always feel

148
00:05:47,660 --> 00:05:49,500
 like it's changing in your world,

149
00:05:49,500 --> 00:05:54,140
 you can be confident that the sun is still shining.

150
00:05:54,140 --> 00:05:59,180
 It all depends on your perspective, however.

151
00:05:59,180 --> 00:06:01,860
 That's how you're able to discern the difference.

152
00:06:01,860 --> 00:06:05,380
 Like that pilot, you've got to get up to an altitude

153
00:06:05,380 --> 00:06:08,580
 where you can see things as they actually are.

154
00:06:08,580 --> 00:06:11,180
 You've got to get up to God's altitude.

155
00:06:11,180 --> 00:06:14,060
 You've got to see from his perspective.

156
00:06:14,060 --> 00:06:16,460
 And as you do, you're able to make sense

157
00:06:16,460 --> 00:06:19,920
 of whatever it is you're truly feeling in life.

158
00:06:19,920 --> 00:06:22,780
 That's what we've been trying to do in this series.

159
00:06:22,780 --> 00:06:24,100
 Like if you're here for the very first time,

160
00:06:24,100 --> 00:06:26,100
 we've been journeying through a series called 2020,

161
00:06:26,100 --> 00:06:28,100
 where we're trying to put your mental health

162
00:06:28,100 --> 00:06:29,500
 into perspective.

163
00:06:29,500 --> 00:06:30,620
 And the way that we've been doing it

164
00:06:30,620 --> 00:06:32,720
 is we've been doing it through the book of Psalms.

165
00:06:32,720 --> 00:06:34,340
 The reason why we've been in the book of Psalms

166
00:06:34,340 --> 00:06:37,100
 is the book of Psalms is sort of,

167
00:06:37,100 --> 00:06:39,980
 it reads kind of like your personal diary.

168
00:06:39,980 --> 00:06:41,040
 Not that you have a personal diary,

169
00:06:41,040 --> 00:06:42,180
 but maybe you had a personal diary.

170
00:06:42,180 --> 00:06:43,420
 It reads like that though.

171
00:06:43,420 --> 00:06:47,500
 It's full of raw emotion, you know, brutal honesty,

172
00:06:47,500 --> 00:06:49,540
 like impassioned, please.

173
00:06:49,540 --> 00:06:52,020
 That's the way the Psalms read out.

174
00:06:52,020 --> 00:06:56,220
 It's like your diary in the sense that it is 100% full

175
00:06:56,220 --> 00:06:57,620
 of emotion.

176
00:06:57,620 --> 00:07:00,400
 And yet the Psalms is unlike your diary

177
00:07:00,400 --> 00:07:05,020
 in that it is also 100% full of truth.

178
00:07:05,020 --> 00:07:08,100
 That's why it's the perfect place to process

179
00:07:08,100 --> 00:07:10,960
 a proper perspective when it comes to our mental

180
00:07:10,960 --> 00:07:13,640
 and emotional health, because we can feel

181
00:07:13,640 --> 00:07:17,000
 all of our feelings and yet we can bring those things

182
00:07:17,000 --> 00:07:20,840
 as the Psalmists do to God's truth.

183
00:07:20,840 --> 00:07:23,320
 And he can speak into them, inform them,

184
00:07:23,320 --> 00:07:25,240
 and ultimately shape the way

185
00:07:25,240 --> 00:07:28,380
 that we walk through this world.

186
00:07:28,380 --> 00:07:30,640
 And so what we're doing over the course of the series

187
00:07:30,640 --> 00:07:34,120
 is we're really framing around the top five

188
00:07:34,120 --> 00:07:38,940
 mental health challenges most common amongst Americans today.

189
00:07:38,940 --> 00:07:40,960
 The first week was all about depression.

190
00:07:40,960 --> 00:07:42,640
 The second week was all about anxiety.

191
00:07:42,640 --> 00:07:45,800
 And tonight we're gonna be talking about addiction,

192
00:07:45,800 --> 00:07:48,920
 addiction and indulgence.

193
00:07:48,920 --> 00:07:52,800
 And to unpack it, we're gonna be looking at Psalm 141.

194
00:07:52,800 --> 00:07:54,680
 So if you've got a Bible, you can turn with me there.

195
00:07:54,680 --> 00:07:58,300
 Psalm 141, while you're doing that, let me just say this,

196
00:07:58,300 --> 00:08:02,720
 because it's important to be said week after week.

197
00:08:02,720 --> 00:08:04,080
 We know our depth up here.

198
00:08:04,080 --> 00:08:05,120
 Like I'm not a doctor.

199
00:08:05,120 --> 00:08:07,480
 There's no part of me that is trying to diagnose

200
00:08:07,480 --> 00:08:09,200
 what it is you're dealing with.

201
00:08:09,200 --> 00:08:11,880
 Like I feel very comfortable and confident

202
00:08:11,880 --> 00:08:14,780
 from the scripture to speak into a variety

203
00:08:14,780 --> 00:08:18,100
 of situational sorts of circumstances.

204
00:08:18,100 --> 00:08:21,040
 And yet many of you here, you may find yourself

205
00:08:21,040 --> 00:08:23,700
 beyond the bounds of a situational

206
00:08:23,700 --> 00:08:24,780
 type of mental health challenge.

207
00:08:24,780 --> 00:08:26,580
 You might be facing something that is clinical.

208
00:08:26,580 --> 00:08:29,220
 Instead, if that's you, what I want you to know is

209
00:08:29,220 --> 00:08:32,600
 the truth of God's word will be vital for your healing.

210
00:08:32,600 --> 00:08:36,980
 But that doesn't mean it's mutually exclusive

211
00:08:36,980 --> 00:08:38,640
 to the treatment plan or recommendations made

212
00:08:38,640 --> 00:08:40,160
 by your doctor.

213
00:08:40,160 --> 00:08:44,580
 Like the scripture and your prescription,

214
00:08:44,580 --> 00:08:46,620
 they can work in partnership together.

215
00:08:46,620 --> 00:08:49,980
 They can be a part of your healing journey.

216
00:08:49,980 --> 00:08:51,580
 And I also wanna say that if you're here tonight

217
00:08:51,580 --> 00:08:53,720
 and you would consider yourself an addict,

218
00:08:53,720 --> 00:08:55,360
 maybe you've been diagnosed as such,

219
00:08:55,360 --> 00:08:58,880
 or maybe you're self-diagnosed as such,

220
00:08:58,880 --> 00:09:02,580
 I just want you to hear nowhere in this message

221
00:09:02,580 --> 00:09:05,480
 are you going to hear me say, you just need to stop that.

222
00:09:06,460 --> 00:09:09,900
 Because that would imply that you have the strength

223
00:09:09,900 --> 00:09:13,460
 to overcome your addiction all on your own.

224
00:09:13,460 --> 00:09:16,940
 And the truth is many addicts do not have the strength

225
00:09:16,940 --> 00:09:17,780
 to do that.

226
00:09:17,780 --> 00:09:20,580
 Instead, they need to rely on the strength of others.

227
00:09:20,580 --> 00:09:23,220
 And so I want to stand before you right now.

228
00:09:23,220 --> 00:09:27,300
 And if that's you, I just wanna plead with you.

229
00:09:27,300 --> 00:09:30,700
 Would you let us be strong for you?

230
00:09:30,700 --> 00:09:34,120
 Would you give us the permission to jump into

231
00:09:34,120 --> 00:09:36,560
 whatever it is you're dealing with by visiting with us

232
00:09:36,560 --> 00:09:37,640
 at the end of the night?

233
00:09:37,640 --> 00:09:39,880
 You don't have to necessarily come down front.

234
00:09:39,880 --> 00:09:42,240
 You can find anybody in a black shirt and a lanyard

235
00:09:42,240 --> 00:09:43,480
 and you can just grab them by the hand

236
00:09:43,480 --> 00:09:45,060
 and they'll know like, okay, that means that

237
00:09:45,060 --> 00:09:47,040
 I probably need to visit with you in private,

238
00:09:47,040 --> 00:09:49,560
 pull you over and introduce you to someone on staff.

239
00:09:49,560 --> 00:09:53,280
 But we're really serious about helping you make good strides

240
00:09:53,280 --> 00:09:56,360
 when it comes to the topic of your addiction.

241
00:09:56,360 --> 00:09:58,200
 Now, with all of that said,

242
00:09:58,200 --> 00:10:00,540
 how do we get a proper perspective on addiction,

243
00:10:00,540 --> 00:10:02,440
 on indulgence?

244
00:10:02,440 --> 00:10:03,280
 Well, first and foremost,

245
00:10:03,280 --> 00:10:05,280
 we have to understand the problem of it.

246
00:10:05,280 --> 00:10:07,280
 That's where we've begun all of these talks.

247
00:10:07,280 --> 00:10:08,760
 That's where we're beginning here tonight.

248
00:10:08,760 --> 00:10:11,680
 We need to understand that addiction is a bigger deal

249
00:10:11,680 --> 00:10:13,780
 and danger than most of us realize.

250
00:10:13,780 --> 00:10:15,420
 So if you've been tracking the headlines

251
00:10:15,420 --> 00:10:17,960
 and you may already know this, but in case you haven't,

252
00:10:17,960 --> 00:10:19,820
 we are, according to many researchers,

253
00:10:19,820 --> 00:10:23,920
 facing what they're calling an addiction crisis.

254
00:10:23,920 --> 00:10:24,960
 According to Shatterproof,

255
00:10:24,960 --> 00:10:26,680
 one of the leading nonprofit organizations

256
00:10:26,680 --> 00:10:29,240
 that's committed to ending addiction in our country.

257
00:10:29,240 --> 00:10:32,760
 Hear this, nearly 49 million Americans.

258
00:10:32,760 --> 00:10:37,760
 I repeat, nearly 49 million Americans, ages 12 or older,

259
00:10:37,760 --> 00:10:41,760
 had a substance use addiction in the past year.

260
00:10:41,760 --> 00:10:46,080
 Meaning they rely on things like alcohol and cannabis

261
00:10:46,080 --> 00:10:49,520
 and cocaine and methamphetamine and opioids.

262
00:10:49,520 --> 00:10:52,160
 They rely on all manner of different substances

263
00:10:52,160 --> 00:10:53,640
 to provide them the kind of comfort

264
00:10:53,640 --> 00:10:55,820
 they cannot find elsewhere.

265
00:10:55,820 --> 00:10:57,520
 To put that into perspective for you,

266
00:10:57,520 --> 00:11:01,400
 'cause 49 million may feel a little bit ethereal.

267
00:11:01,400 --> 00:11:03,480
 That means nearly one in six people

268
00:11:03,480 --> 00:11:06,980
 are living in substance dependence today.

269
00:11:06,980 --> 00:11:09,640
 Making it likely that you and I will encounter someone

270
00:11:09,640 --> 00:11:13,020
 that either has or will have some sort of substance use

271
00:11:13,020 --> 00:11:15,100
 disorder in their life.

272
00:11:15,100 --> 00:11:17,260
 Now you may be sitting here and thinking to yourself,

273
00:11:17,260 --> 00:11:19,180
 but Kyle and I don't struggle with that.

274
00:11:19,180 --> 00:11:21,320
 So this doesn't feel relevant to me at all.

275
00:11:21,320 --> 00:11:22,760
 Well, before you tune me out,

276
00:11:22,760 --> 00:11:25,720
 that's only half of what we're discussing tonight.

277
00:11:25,720 --> 00:11:27,600
 Because what you need to also know

278
00:11:27,600 --> 00:11:29,760
 is that while there is substance use addiction,

279
00:11:29,760 --> 00:11:33,480
 there's also something else called behavioral addiction.

280
00:11:33,480 --> 00:11:36,840
 Track with me here, because this one's far more prevalent.

281
00:11:36,840 --> 00:11:39,760
 Behavioral addiction is like substance addiction,

282
00:11:39,760 --> 00:11:43,600
 except it's not being addicted to drugs or alcohol.

283
00:11:43,600 --> 00:11:48,160
 Instead, the individual is addicted to a particular behavior

284
00:11:48,160 --> 00:11:51,060
 in the feelings that are evoked from that behavior

285
00:11:51,060 --> 00:11:54,820
 that lead them to a place where they lack self-control.

286
00:11:54,820 --> 00:11:57,560
 So see if you identify potentially.

287
00:11:57,560 --> 00:11:59,440
 Behavioral addiction can include things like

288
00:11:59,440 --> 00:12:03,160
 social media, pornography, cell phone use,

289
00:12:03,160 --> 00:12:07,560
 video gaming, workaholism, food, compulsive shopping,

290
00:12:07,560 --> 00:12:11,760
 exercise, who would have thought, self-harm, and gambling.

291
00:12:11,760 --> 00:12:15,480
 All of these things can be damaging to your mental health.

292
00:12:15,480 --> 00:12:17,120
 Now, why do I share all that with you?

293
00:12:17,120 --> 00:12:18,040
 Some of you are sitting here, you're like,

294
00:12:18,040 --> 00:12:20,640
 dude, just get into Psalm 141.

295
00:12:20,640 --> 00:12:22,840
 We're going to, just bear with me.

296
00:12:22,840 --> 00:12:26,580
 It's important for us to understand this warning

297
00:12:26,580 --> 00:12:29,960
 that none of us are as safe as we think we are

298
00:12:29,960 --> 00:12:32,820
 when it comes to the topic of addiction.

299
00:12:32,820 --> 00:12:36,520
 Like, you think anybody ever intends

300
00:12:36,520 --> 00:12:40,660
 to enslave themselves to some sort of indulgence?

301
00:12:40,660 --> 00:12:42,760
 No, of course they don't.

302
00:12:42,760 --> 00:12:44,660
 Nobody is ever intending, you know what?

303
00:12:44,660 --> 00:12:46,180
 Like, I do think I'll be an alcoholic.

304
00:12:46,180 --> 00:12:47,380
 That sounds like a nice way of living.

305
00:12:47,380 --> 00:12:48,980
 Nobody is intending to do that.

306
00:12:48,980 --> 00:12:50,900
 And we laugh, and yet the reality is,

307
00:12:50,900 --> 00:12:53,180
 this thing comes for all of us

308
00:12:53,180 --> 00:12:55,480
 in a way where it doesn't just suddenly show up.

309
00:12:55,480 --> 00:12:57,820
 Instead, it gradually creeps in.

310
00:12:57,820 --> 00:13:00,700
 It's like the free app on your phone

311
00:13:00,700 --> 00:13:04,180
 that you download because, ah, that thing's harmless.

312
00:13:04,180 --> 00:13:06,900
 And yet, it's draining your battery.

313
00:13:06,900 --> 00:13:08,540
 It's stealing your data.

314
00:13:08,540 --> 00:13:10,180
 It's waking you up at two in the morning.

315
00:13:10,180 --> 00:13:11,220
 Like, that's what's happening.

316
00:13:11,220 --> 00:13:14,020
 It's creeped into your life under the premise

317
00:13:14,020 --> 00:13:16,900
 that it is harmless, and yet it's actually come

318
00:13:16,900 --> 00:13:20,200
 to disrupt everything about your reality.

319
00:13:20,200 --> 00:13:23,740
 And so we've got to know, what do we do with it?

320
00:13:23,740 --> 00:13:26,920
 Like, how do we actually move away from it?

321
00:13:26,920 --> 00:13:27,760
 Well, we're gonna get to that,

322
00:13:27,760 --> 00:13:30,040
 but what we have to understand first and foremost,

323
00:13:30,040 --> 00:13:32,480
 and David actually shares this with us,

324
00:13:32,480 --> 00:13:35,280
 is that addiction, it takes root

325
00:13:35,280 --> 00:13:38,280
 because it appeals to your reward system.

326
00:13:38,280 --> 00:13:40,280
 A really simple way of understanding that

327
00:13:40,280 --> 00:13:42,560
 is it feels good to be bad.

328
00:13:42,560 --> 00:13:43,820
 That's what happens.

329
00:13:43,820 --> 00:13:46,040
 So think of it like this.

330
00:13:46,040 --> 00:13:48,400
 Not everyone that drinks Doomscrolls

331
00:13:48,400 --> 00:13:50,240
 and watches pornography does it because,

332
00:13:50,240 --> 00:13:52,440
 man, they just wanna be a really addicted individual.

333
00:13:52,440 --> 00:13:55,760
 No, they do it because they're trying to reduce stress,

334
00:13:55,760 --> 00:13:58,560
 loneliness, discomfort.

335
00:13:58,560 --> 00:14:01,600
 A lot of people that work in high-stress,

336
00:14:01,600 --> 00:14:04,320
 fast-paced corporate environments,

337
00:14:04,320 --> 00:14:07,080
 they will find themselves using things like alcohol

338
00:14:07,080 --> 00:14:11,080
 and prescription medication and stimulants

339
00:14:11,080 --> 00:14:14,160
 because they ultimately know what it takes

340
00:14:14,160 --> 00:14:15,720
 to keep up in this environment.

341
00:14:15,720 --> 00:14:17,000
 They're not doing it because,

342
00:14:17,000 --> 00:14:18,280
 well, that's gonna make mom proud.

343
00:14:18,280 --> 00:14:21,280
 Instead, they're doing it because that's the price

344
00:14:21,280 --> 00:14:24,280
 they have to pay to be productive.

345
00:14:24,280 --> 00:14:26,480
 Any procrastinators in the room?

346
00:14:26,480 --> 00:14:28,360
 Why are you a procrastinator?

347
00:14:28,360 --> 00:14:31,080
 Is it just because you want everybody to be waiting on you?

348
00:14:31,080 --> 00:14:31,920
 No.

349
00:14:31,920 --> 00:14:34,160
 Is it because you love to watch the world burn?

350
00:14:34,160 --> 00:14:35,000
 Some of you.

351
00:14:35,000 --> 00:14:38,800
 But really, the reason so many of you are procrastinators

352
00:14:38,800 --> 00:14:41,560
 is because you're a perfectionist.

353
00:14:41,560 --> 00:14:44,960
 And so you're trying to reduce the anxiety

354
00:14:44,960 --> 00:14:47,600
 and the frustrations you feel about completing a task

355
00:14:47,600 --> 00:14:51,000
 that is less than the standard you actually want to achieve.

356
00:14:51,000 --> 00:14:52,720
 Do you see how it works?

357
00:14:52,720 --> 00:14:57,720
 It feels good, leaves you rewarded to do bad.

358
00:14:57,720 --> 00:15:00,560
 And we see David wrestling with that very reality

359
00:15:00,560 --> 00:15:02,360
 in Psalm 141.

360
00:15:02,360 --> 00:15:04,240
 Now, as we set this passage up,

361
00:15:04,240 --> 00:15:06,920
 what you need to know is the context of it is debated.

362
00:15:06,920 --> 00:15:09,200
 We don't necessarily know for certain

363
00:15:09,200 --> 00:15:11,000
 what the situation around David is.

364
00:15:11,000 --> 00:15:12,240
 And yet as we read through it,

365
00:15:12,240 --> 00:15:14,400
 you can sort of pick out some context clues

366
00:15:14,400 --> 00:15:16,760
 to help you guess where he may be

367
00:15:16,760 --> 00:15:18,400
 and what may be happening.

368
00:15:19,240 --> 00:15:21,440
 Scholars, they land in one of two places.

369
00:15:21,440 --> 00:15:24,560
 They either think that he is being pursued by King Saul

370
00:15:24,560 --> 00:15:29,560
 in his youth or King Absalom following his kingship.

371
00:15:29,560 --> 00:15:32,040
 And what you need to know is

372
00:15:32,040 --> 00:15:33,560
 neither one of them ultimately really matter

373
00:15:33,560 --> 00:15:36,800
 because what we can understand is they are both marked

374
00:15:36,800 --> 00:15:39,040
 by a similar set of circumstances.

375
00:15:39,040 --> 00:15:40,840
 The guy's being hunted down.

376
00:15:40,840 --> 00:15:43,000
 Tough day at the office, right?

377
00:15:43,000 --> 00:15:44,400
 Like he's being hunted down.

378
00:15:44,400 --> 00:15:46,760
 He's being pursued by attackers.

379
00:15:46,760 --> 00:15:48,760
 His life is on the line.

380
00:15:48,760 --> 00:15:50,280
 And so what we see him say

381
00:15:50,280 --> 00:15:53,320
 in the middle of that entire situation in verse three,

382
00:15:53,320 --> 00:15:56,880
 he says, "Set a guard, O Lord, over my mouth.

383
00:15:56,880 --> 00:15:59,280
 Keep watch over the door of my lips.

384
00:15:59,280 --> 00:16:01,480
 Do not let my heart incline to any evil,

385
00:16:01,480 --> 00:16:03,200
 to busy myself with wicked deeds

386
00:16:03,200 --> 00:16:04,920
 in company with men who work iniquity,

387
00:16:04,920 --> 00:16:08,000
 and let me not eat of their delicacies."

388
00:16:08,000 --> 00:16:10,200
 Do you hear the struggle in his voice?

389
00:16:10,200 --> 00:16:13,480
 What David is saying right here is he's saying,

390
00:16:13,480 --> 00:16:15,360
 "I wanna sin.

391
00:16:15,360 --> 00:16:17,560
 Like, I wanna get back.

392
00:16:17,560 --> 00:16:21,520
 I wanna dish back whatever has been dished out to me.

393
00:16:21,520 --> 00:16:23,880
 Like, I want to give them a dose of their own medicine.

394
00:16:23,880 --> 00:16:25,920
 They're trying to pursue me and take me out.

395
00:16:25,920 --> 00:16:27,920
 I wanna pursue them, and I wanna take them out.

396
00:16:27,920 --> 00:16:29,200
 God, that's what I wanna do.

397
00:16:29,200 --> 00:16:32,240
 I'm praying to you because I actually want to sin.

398
00:16:32,240 --> 00:16:33,360
 And so God, what I'm asking is

399
00:16:33,360 --> 00:16:34,920
 that you would guard me from myself."

400
00:16:34,920 --> 00:16:37,160
 That's what he's articulating right here.

401
00:16:37,160 --> 00:16:41,080
 The problem of his indulgence is he wants to retaliate.

402
00:16:41,080 --> 00:16:44,640
 He wants to indulge in evil desire

403
00:16:44,640 --> 00:16:47,600
 against those that have been evil against him.

404
00:16:47,600 --> 00:16:48,560
 And the way that he says,

405
00:16:48,560 --> 00:16:51,120
 "God, would you guard me?" is threefold.

406
00:16:51,120 --> 00:16:53,280
 He asks God, "Would you guard my mouth?

407
00:16:53,280 --> 00:16:54,360
 Would you guard my heart?

408
00:16:54,360 --> 00:16:57,240
 And would you guard my desire?"

409
00:16:57,240 --> 00:16:58,860
 Why is it threefold?

410
00:16:58,860 --> 00:17:02,360
 Because that's the way it works, remember?

411
00:17:02,360 --> 00:17:04,320
 Indulgence creeps in.

412
00:17:04,320 --> 00:17:06,360
 It doesn't just show up.

413
00:17:06,360 --> 00:17:09,120
 It gradually takes hold.

414
00:17:09,120 --> 00:17:11,280
 And so it often begins with our words.

415
00:17:11,280 --> 00:17:15,840
 He says, "Keep watch over the door of my lips."

416
00:17:15,840 --> 00:17:17,320
 Why does he start there?

417
00:17:17,320 --> 00:17:19,200
 "Watch over my mouth, God."

418
00:17:19,200 --> 00:17:23,120
 Because when we say out loud what we feel inside

419
00:17:23,120 --> 00:17:27,480
 is giving our feelings an opportunity

420
00:17:27,480 --> 00:17:29,480
 to become a legitimized to the point

421
00:17:29,480 --> 00:17:31,960
 that we identify with them.

422
00:17:31,960 --> 00:17:33,800
 So I'll give you an example of this.

423
00:17:33,800 --> 00:17:36,000
 I thought it was fascinating a year ago

424
00:17:36,000 --> 00:17:38,320
 during the Paris Olympics.

425
00:17:38,320 --> 00:17:41,460
 Olympians were regularly asked by reporters,

426
00:17:41,460 --> 00:17:42,680
 "Are you nervous?"

427
00:17:42,680 --> 00:17:47,280
 And they would regularly reply, "No, I'm excited."

428
00:17:47,280 --> 00:17:49,400
 Which is fascinating, why?

429
00:17:49,400 --> 00:17:52,600
 Because both nervousness and excitement

430
00:17:52,600 --> 00:17:57,600
 are similar in terms of the physical sensation they produce.

431
00:17:57,600 --> 00:18:02,160
 Gives you clammy hands and a sweaty brow and a racing heart.

432
00:18:02,160 --> 00:18:03,840
 Like that's what ultimately nervousness

433
00:18:03,840 --> 00:18:05,800
 and excitement both do.

434
00:18:05,800 --> 00:18:08,640
 And yet what these Olympians are saying

435
00:18:08,640 --> 00:18:11,600
 is that they want to positively identify with that emotion

436
00:18:11,600 --> 00:18:13,960
 as opposed to negatively identify with that emotion.

437
00:18:13,960 --> 00:18:16,900
 So they're not willing to subscribe

438
00:18:16,900 --> 00:18:18,280
 to the way the reporter is saying it.

439
00:18:18,280 --> 00:18:20,400
 Instead, they want to reframe it

440
00:18:20,400 --> 00:18:22,360
 so they identify with it instead.

441
00:18:22,360 --> 00:18:25,560
 They know what I say is what I'm going to become.

442
00:18:25,560 --> 00:18:28,040
 And so I don't want to be nervous, I want to be excited.

443
00:18:28,040 --> 00:18:29,120
 Makes sense?

444
00:18:29,120 --> 00:18:31,400
 That's why you have to start with your words.

445
00:18:31,400 --> 00:18:34,680
 David is saying in reference to something similar we see

446
00:18:34,680 --> 00:18:36,080
 in the book of James.

447
00:18:36,080 --> 00:18:37,640
 We're not going to read the specific passage.

448
00:18:37,640 --> 00:18:39,880
 You can go look at his James 3, 3-5.

449
00:18:39,880 --> 00:18:43,720
 But we learned that the power of the tongue is extreme.

450
00:18:43,720 --> 00:18:46,360
 It's like a bit in the mouth of a horse.

451
00:18:46,360 --> 00:18:48,480
 It's like a rudder on the tail of a ship.

452
00:18:48,480 --> 00:18:51,080
 It's like a fire that can set the whole forest ablaze.

453
00:18:51,080 --> 00:18:56,080
 Like it has great power to change the whole of something.

454
00:18:56,080 --> 00:18:59,600
 So too does your mouth have that kind of power.

455
00:18:59,600 --> 00:19:01,040
 But it doesn't stop there.

456
00:19:01,040 --> 00:19:03,960
 It doesn't just affect your words, it affects your deeds.

457
00:19:03,960 --> 00:19:07,560
 He says, "Do not let my heart incline to any evil."

458
00:19:07,560 --> 00:19:11,000
 In the West, when we read the word heart,

459
00:19:11,000 --> 00:19:13,240
 we think Valentine's Day and the things that I feel.

460
00:19:13,240 --> 00:19:15,440
 Butterflies inside, love for other people.

461
00:19:15,440 --> 00:19:17,720
 You know, like we think it's all about emotion.

462
00:19:17,720 --> 00:19:19,720
 And yet what we know is the heart

463
00:19:19,720 --> 00:19:21,840
 in the ancient near Eastern mind is not about emotion

464
00:19:21,840 --> 00:19:23,920
 as much as it is about action.

465
00:19:23,920 --> 00:19:26,240
 It's the seat of the will,

466
00:19:26,240 --> 00:19:28,160
 which is basically the place

467
00:19:28,160 --> 00:19:31,280
 from which you make decisions in life.

468
00:19:31,280 --> 00:19:33,680
 And so David is saying here, he's like,

469
00:19:33,680 --> 00:19:38,000
 "Hey, I don't just feel temptation to slander my enemies,

470
00:19:38,000 --> 00:19:40,560
 to use my mouth, to tear them down.

471
00:19:40,560 --> 00:19:43,240
 I also feel the urge to retaliate against them,

472
00:19:43,240 --> 00:19:45,240
 to take swift action,

473
00:19:45,240 --> 00:19:48,280
 to dish back what they've dished to me."

474
00:19:48,280 --> 00:19:50,240
 But it doesn't just stop there.

475
00:19:50,240 --> 00:19:52,640
 Begins with his words, it moves to his deeds,

476
00:19:52,640 --> 00:19:55,760
 and then it creeps into his desire.

477
00:19:55,760 --> 00:19:59,560
 He says, "Let me not eat of their delicacies."

478
00:19:59,560 --> 00:20:02,360
 It's a really important part of the verse

479
00:20:02,360 --> 00:20:03,880
 because it tells us something important

480
00:20:03,880 --> 00:20:06,120
 about the way that sin works.

481
00:20:06,120 --> 00:20:10,400
 Sin doesn't just want you to do evil.

482
00:20:10,400 --> 00:20:12,800
 Sin wants you to delight in evil.

483
00:20:12,800 --> 00:20:15,800
 It wants you to love it.

484
00:20:15,800 --> 00:20:18,640
 That's why it feels bad

485
00:20:18,640 --> 00:20:20,800
 or it feels good to do something bad.

486
00:20:20,800 --> 00:20:25,800
 Remember, ultimately it wants to appeal to your pleasure.

487
00:20:25,800 --> 00:20:27,320
 It's a delicacy.

488
00:20:27,320 --> 00:20:30,800
 It's a delight to the taste,

489
00:20:30,800 --> 00:20:32,200
 which is really important

490
00:20:32,200 --> 00:20:34,800
 because it teaches us something we need to understand

491
00:20:34,800 --> 00:20:38,320
 about indulgence or temptation or addiction, ultimately.

492
00:20:38,320 --> 00:20:42,400
 We need to know it's rarely about the substance.

493
00:20:42,400 --> 00:20:46,600
 Instead, it's about what the substance represents.

494
00:20:46,600 --> 00:20:49,560
 What I mean by that is,

495
00:20:49,560 --> 00:20:55,640
 David was not just intent to take these guys out.

496
00:20:55,640 --> 00:20:58,960
 He was willing to do that

497
00:20:58,960 --> 00:21:02,000
 if it afforded him peace from his anxiety,

498
00:21:02,000 --> 00:21:03,960
 freedom from their pursuit,

499
00:21:03,960 --> 00:21:05,280
 and hope of a brand new future.

500
00:21:05,280 --> 00:21:06,640
 See how that works?

501
00:21:06,640 --> 00:21:08,960
 He's not just focused on the substance.

502
00:21:08,960 --> 00:21:11,160
 He's focused on what the substance represents.

503
00:21:11,160 --> 00:21:14,920
 And that's the way it works for everybody.

504
00:21:14,920 --> 00:21:18,920
 Like whether it's behavioral or it is substance,

505
00:21:18,920 --> 00:21:23,480
 pornography, excessive shopping,

506
00:21:23,480 --> 00:21:27,280
 eating disorders, opioid addiction, it doesn't matter.

507
00:21:27,280 --> 00:21:29,760
 Across the range of it all,

508
00:21:29,760 --> 00:21:30,600
 it's never about the substance.

509
00:21:30,600 --> 00:21:32,480
 It's about what the substance represents.

510
00:21:32,480 --> 00:21:34,240
 Oh, well, that gives me relief.

511
00:21:34,240 --> 00:21:35,440
 Well, that provides me comfort.

512
00:21:35,440 --> 00:21:38,800
 Well, I feel a sense of belonging whenever I do that.

513
00:21:38,800 --> 00:21:41,040
 I get freedom whenever I find myself

514
00:21:41,040 --> 00:21:43,240
 actually participating in that activity.

515
00:21:43,240 --> 00:21:44,400
 I get validation.

516
00:21:44,400 --> 00:21:46,040
 I matter whenever I do that.

517
00:21:46,040 --> 00:21:47,120
 See how it works?

518
00:21:47,120 --> 00:21:51,640
 But what if I told you,

519
00:21:51,640 --> 00:21:55,600
 you could find all of that and more without the substance?

520
00:21:55,600 --> 00:21:58,040
 What if I told you there was a way to feel good

521
00:21:58,040 --> 00:22:00,960
 by doing good?

522
00:22:00,960 --> 00:22:03,600
 What if I told you there was a way

523
00:22:03,600 --> 00:22:05,520
 to change your perspective altogether?

524
00:22:05,520 --> 00:22:10,840
 Well, that's what the rest of Psalm 141 is all about.

525
00:22:10,840 --> 00:22:11,960
